Symboling
It is the measure of the risk associated with the vehicle, a higher value means high risk.
The values can be in the range of -3 to +3 (both included). This poses a problem since there are both positive and negative values which will make it hard to interpret the coefficient of this variable.

One thing that can be done is to make all the values positive by adding +3 to the entire column, so that:
-3 becomes 0 and +3 becomes 6.
This means that we've changed the range from [-3,3] to [0,6] which is easily interpretable.

In [16]:
cars['symboling']=cars['symboling']+3

Although we get an R-squared value of 0.93 which is great, we also have a lot of variables that are insignificant since their p-value are very high.
From the correlation plot we made earlier, we know that some variables such as enginesize, curbweight, horsepower, etc have a really high correlation (>0.75) and therefore by intuition these should be significant in the model.
There seems to be a problem of multicollinearity, and therefore we must also find the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) to account for it.

Calculating the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF):¶

In [64]:
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor
In [65]:

vif['VIF'] = round(vif['VIF'], 2)
vif = vif.sort_values('VIF', ascending = False)

We can see that the VIF tends to infinity for the variables idi and fueltype.
This is because the R2 of the model built by using these variables alone would be 1 and therefore according to the formula for VIF which is 1/(1-R2), the VIF will tend to infinity.
Below is the correlation between the two variables which is equal to 1 which means that there is a perfect collinearity between the two variables.

In [66]:

Now that we have valid values in the VIF table, let us begin training the model, i.e selecting the variables that are significant.

The steps that have been followed to train the model are as follows:¶

  • The variables having a high VIF and a high p-value have been removed first (one variable at a time).
  • After the above step is done, the variables having a high p-value and a low VIF are removed (also one variable at a time).
  • After the above two steps are done, the variables with low p-value and a high VIF are removed.

After the completion of the above mentioned steps, we are left only with those variables which are highly significant (i.e low p-value and low VIF (<5)) and also the problem of multicollinearity, if any, would not be present anymore.

Let us continue with the bottom-up approach and cherry pick all the variables with high VIF and high p-values.¶

The regression equation will be:
price = 0.0816(b1) + 0.1903(b2)+ 1.1069(b3) + 0.0973(b4) + 0.1896(b5) - 0.1388

b1 = fueltype
b2 = enginelocation
b3 = enginesize
b4 = peakrpm
b5 = rotor

Comparison of Manual and Automated Variable Selection:¶

Manual Variable Selection:¶

The Manual variable selection gave the following regression line:
price = 0.0591(b1) + 0.02245(b2) + 1.1244(b3) - 0.0032(b4) - 0.0346(b5) - 0.1054(b6) + 0.2510(b7) - 0.0340
R2 = 0.861
Adjusted R2 = 0.854

where:
b1 = aspiration
b2 = enginelocation
b3 = enginesize
b4 = Company_Name
b5 = hatchback
b6 = ohcv
b7 = rotor

Automated Variable Selection:¶

The regression equation will be:
price = 0.0816(b1) + 0.1903(b2)+ 1.1069(b3) + 0.0973(b4) + 0.1896(b5) - 0.1388
R2 = 0.835
Adjusted R2 = 0.829
where:
b1 = fueltype
b2 = enginelocation
b3 = enginesize
b4 = peakrpm
b5 = rotor

We can see that the variables enginesize, enginelocation and rotor are common across the two models which means that they are significant.
Let us now try creating a model with all the above variables and see which of them are the most significant.

Comparison of all the 3 models (Manual, RFE and Combined)¶

Manual Variable Selection:¶

The Manual variable selection gives the following regression line:
price = 0.0591(b1) + 0.02245(b2) + 1.1244(b3) - 0.0032(b4) - 0.0346(b5) - 0.1054(b6) + 0.2510(b7) - 0.0340

Test R2 = 0.828

b1 = aspiration
b2 = enginelocation
b3 = enginesize
b4 = Company_Name
b5 = hatchback
b6 = ohcv
b7 = rotor

Automated Variable Selection:¶

The regression equation will be:
price = 0.0816(b1) + 0.1903(b2)+ 1.1069(b3) + 0.0973(b4) + 0.1896(b5) - 0.1388
R2 = 0.835
Adjusted R2 = 0.829
Test R2 = 0.807
where:
b1 = fueltype
b2 = enginelocation
b3 = enginesize
b4 = peakrpm
b5 = rotor

Combined Variable Selection:¶

The regression equation will be:
price = 0.0545(b1) + 0.02248(b2) + 1.1618(b3) - 0.0031(b4) - 0.1204(b5) + 0.2342(b6) - 0.0541
R2 = 0.855
Adjusted R2 = 0.848
Test R2 = 0.816
where:
b1 = aspiration
b2 = enginelocation
b3 = enginesize
b4 = Company_Name
b5 = ohcv
b6 = rotor

From the above comparison it becomes clear that the model obtained by all 3 methods have almost the same level of accuracy, however the Adjusted R2 for Model 1 (Manual variable selection) is higher than the other two models and it is also capable of generalizing the regression line on the test dataset.
Therefore model 1 would be the best choice in this case.
